This is the core hard problem — everything else about the loader is straightforward engineering, but this is where you're fighting an adversary (Valve's minifier and update cadence) with no cooperation. Let me search for what the current state of the art looks like before we design around it.

Good searches — Vencord is the gold standard here. They've been solving this exact problem for Discord for years, and the parallels are almost perfect. Let me map everything across.

---

## The Root of the Fragility Problem

It helps to be precise about *what* actually breaks. There are three distinct failure modes, each needing a different solution:

**1. Module IDs change** — webpack assigns numeric IDs to chunks. If Valve adds or reorganises code, all IDs shift. Any code that does `__webpack_modules__[12345]` directly is dead. This is the worst kind of breakage.

**2. Prop names change** — Valve's minifier renames exported properties. A component exported as `{ SliderField }` becomes `{ ab }`. Finding by `findByProps("SliderField")` stops working.

**3. Component structure changes** — Valve rewrites the component itself. The shape of the rendered output, what props it accepts, how it hooks into the router — all of it can change. You can see this in the Decky changelog: `fix(DialogHeader): valve rewrote component on beta, update filter` and `fix(modals): fix ConfirmModal for new Steam beta` — these are reactive patches to Valve changes.

Each needs a different countermeasure.

---

## Strategy 1: Multi-Criteria Module Finding (Never Use Numeric IDs)

The core insight from Vencord is that you should find modules by **what they do**, not where they live in the chunk graph. The technique is to walk the entire webpack module registry and test each module against one or more predicates:

```ts
// webpack.ts — the module discovery layer, runs inside CEF

function getAllModules(): unknown[] {
  // The chunk array name differs per app (discord uses webpackChunkdiscord_app,
  // Steam uses webpackChunksteamui). We push a sentinel module to read the registry.
  const registry: Record<string, { exports: unknown }> = {};

  (window as any).webpackChunksteamui.push([
    [Symbol()],   // fake chunk id
    {},           // fake module map
    (require: any) => Object.assign(registry, require.c)
  ]);

  return Object.values(registry)
    .map(m => m?.exports)
    .filter(Boolean);
}

// Find by property names on the export
export function findByProps(...props: string[]): unknown {
  return getAllModules().find(mod => {
    if (!mod || mod === window) return false;
    // Check direct export
    if (props.every(p => p in (mod as any))) return mod;
    // Check .default export (common pattern)
    if (props.every(p => p in ((mod as any).default ?? {}))) return (mod as any).default;
  });
}

// Find by a string that appears in the module's source code
// This is MORE stable than prop names — semantic strings survive minification
export function findByCode(...strings: string[]): unknown {
  return getAllModules().find(mod => {
    const code = String(mod);
    return strings.every(s => code.includes(s));
  });
}

// Multi-strategy: try several finders in order, return first that works
export function findWithFallbacks<T>(...finders: Array<() => T | undefined>): T | null {
  for (const finder of finders) {
    try {
      const result = finder();
      if (result) return result;
    } catch { /* try next */ }
  }
  return null;
}
```

Then your component map becomes:

```ts
// steam-modules.ts — the maintained map of all Steam UI components

export const SliderField = findWithFallbacks(
  // Primary: find by the string "SliderField" appearing in source (survives prop rename)
  () => findByCode("SliderField", "notchCount", "notchTicksVisible"),
  // Fallback 1: find by current known prop names
  () => findByProps("SliderField")?.SliderField,
  // Fallback 2: find by the very distinctive notch rendering logic
  () => findByCode("renderNotchTick", "stepSize")
);
```

The Vencord guidance is explicit: do not rely on minified variable names like `e` or `n` in your finders — those can change at any time. Instead, find modules by semantic strings that are meaningful enough that Valve would have to deliberately rename them. Things like `"SliderField"`, `"notchTicksVisible"`, `"RegisterForGameActionStart"` — these are developer-named strings in Valve's source that survive minification because they're string literals, not identifiers.

---

## Strategy 2: Lazy Module Proxies (Never Block on Module Resolution)

The other Vencord innovation that matters hugely: instead of resolving modules eagerly at startup (which fails if a chunk hasn't loaded yet, or if your injection runs before a module registers), you return a **Proxy** that defers resolution until first access:

```ts
// The module might not be registered yet when the loader injects.
// A Proxy lets you hand out a reference immediately and resolve it lazily.

export function findLazy<T extends object>(...finders: Array<() => T | undefined>): T {
  let resolved: T | null = null;

  return new Proxy({} as T, {
    get(_, prop) {
      if (!resolved) {
        resolved = findWithFallbacks(...finders);
        if (!resolved) {
          // Log it but don't throw — other plugins shouldn't crash
          console.warn(`[loadout] Module not found for prop: ${String(prop)}`);
          return undefined;
        }
      }
      return (resolved as any)[prop];
    }
  });
}

// Usage — SliderField is handed out immediately, resolved on first render
export const SliderField = findLazy(
  () => findByCode("SliderField", "notchCount"),
  () => findByProps("SliderField")?.SliderField,
);
```

This means plugin code that does `import { SliderField } from "@loadout/ui"` never throws at import time. If Steam hasn't registered that module yet, it just returns `undefined` on first access — which React handles gracefully, and which gives you a clean warning to work with rather than a crash.

---

## Strategy 3: Code-String Patching (Vencord's Biggest Insight)

This is the genuinely clever part that Vencord figured out and that Decky hasn't fully adopted. Instead of finding a module and then monkey-patching it with `original = module.fn; module.fn = (...args) => { /* wrap */ return original(...args) }` — which breaks when the module shape changes — you intercept webpack's **module registration** and rewrite the module's source code before it executes.

Vencord uses a different approach from monkey-patching webpack: it directly modifies the code before the target app loads it, using a `find` value as a unique string to identify the module, then a `match`/`replace` regex pair to rewrite it.

Translated to Steam's context:

```ts
// patcher.ts — intercepts webpack module registration

interface Patch {
  // A string that must appear in the module source to identify it uniquely
  find: string;
  replacement: {
    match: RegExp;
    replace: string;
  };
}

const patches: Patch[] = [];

function installWebpackInterceptor() {
  const originalPush = (window as any).webpackChunksteamui.push.bind(
    (window as any).webpackChunksteamui
  );

  (window as any).webpackChunksteamui.push = function(chunk: any[]) {
    // chunk[1] is the module factory map: { moduleId: (module, exports, require) => ... }
    if (chunk[1]) {
      for (const [id, factory] of Object.entries(chunk[1])) {
        const factoryStr = String(factory);

        for (const patch of patches) {
          if (factoryStr.includes(patch.find)) {
            // Rewrite the module source before it executes
            const patched = factoryStr.replace(patch.replacement.match, patch.replacement.replace);
            (chunk[1] as any)[id] = new Function(
              "module", "exports", "require",
              patched.slice(patched.indexOf("{") + 1, patched.lastIndexOf("}"))
            );
          }
        }
      }
    }

    return originalPush(chunk);
  };
}

// Example: inject a custom component into Steam's QAM render
patches.push({
  find: "QuickAccessMenu", // unique string in the module
  replacement: {
    match: /(\w+\.push\(\{key:"notifications")/, // find the notifications tab push
    replace: `SteamLoader.renderPluginTabs(),$1` // inject before it
  }
});
```

This is radically more robust than monkey-patching for a key reason: the patch is applied *before* the module runs, so there's no timing issue, no race with React reconciliation, and no issue with the module being frozen or sealed. The `find` string locates the module; the regex rewrites one surgical line. If Valve changes the surrounding code but keeps the semantic meaning, your regex still matches because it targets a specific, meaningful string rather than minified variable names.

---

## Strategy 4: Automated Compatibility CI

Vencord has a Reporter system — a dedicated test mode that loads all webpack chunks, then validates that every `findByProps` and `findByCode` call resolves to exactly one module, and that every patch actually matches and compiles correctly. It logs failures like `Webpack Find Fail: findByProps("bar", "baz")` clearly.

You can do this too, because the Steam CEF context is remotely debuggable. A CI job could:

1. Launch a Steam instance (Valve provides a way to run the Steam Deck UI on desktop)
2. Connect to the CEF debug port
3. Inject your test harness
4. Run `validateAllModules()` which tests every entry in `steam-modules.ts`
5. Report which finders are broken

This turns "random breakage after a SteamOS update" into "a CI job fails and you get a PR with the broken finders listed". The entire health of your Steam UI integration becomes visible before a release.

---

## The UI Library Question: Extract vs Build Your Own

This is the most interesting design decision. You have three real options:

**Option A: Re-export Steam's extracted components (what @decky/ui does)**

Extract `SliderField`, `Toggle`, `DialogButton`, `Focusable`, etc. from Steam's webpack registry and re-export them under stable names. Plugins import `@your-loader/ui` and get Steam's actual components. They look pixel-perfect because *they are* Steam's components.

The weakness: when Valve rewrites a component, all plugins using it break until you push a loader update. This happens regularly — you can see constant `fix(component): valve rewrote X` commits in the @decky/ui changelog.

**Option B: Your own component library, Steam-styled**

Build your own `SliderField`, `Toggle`, `Panel`, etc. using plain React + CSS that visually matches Steam's design language. Plugins are completely isolated from Valve's component churn.

The weakness: you have to do the design work, and there will always be subtle visual differences. Also, Valve updates their visual design occasionally and you have to track it.

**Option C: Hybrid (the right answer)**

This is what a mature loader should do:

- For **purely structural/layout components** (`Panel`, `Section`, `Focusable`, `ContextMenu`, `DialogButton`) — build your own. These are mostly CSS, they're stable to maintain, and plugins don't need Valve's exact implementation.

- For **components with deep Steam integration** (`SliderField` with its hardware notch snapping, `GamepadFocusNavigation`, the gamepad input handling) — extract from Steam with multi-strategy finders and lazy proxies.

- For **interactive navigation** (`Router`, `openModal`, `showContextMenu`) — wrap Steam's APIs with a stable interface layer that absorbs the implementation churn.

The key is that **plugins never directly import Steam internals**. They always go through your `@your-loader/ui` abstraction layer. When Valve breaks something, you fix it once in the layer and every plugin keeps working.

```ts
// @your-loader/ui — what plugin authors import

// These are YOUR components — never break
export { Panel } from "./components/Panel";
export { Section } from "./components/Section";
export { Toggle } from "./components/Toggle";

// These wrap Steam's — may need updates but isolated to the layer
export { SliderField } from "./steam-compat/SliderField";
export { showContextMenu } from "./steam-compat/contextMenu";

// This is a stable wrapper over Steam's router
export { navigate } from "./steam-compat/navigation";
```

---

## What Your Own Component Library Buys You

There's an underappreciated bonus here: if your UI components are your own, you can style them using CSS variables that match Steam's design tokens rather than Steam's actual class names. Steam's class names are webpack-hashed (they look like `Panel_3RNGB`), which means they change. But the *visual values* — colors, spacing, border radii, font sizes — are relatively stable.

You extract the design tokens once:

```ts
// At runtime, read Steam's CSS variables from the computed stylesheet
const steamTokens = {
  bgPrimary: getComputedStyle(document.documentElement)
    .getPropertyValue("--main-editor-bg"),
  accentColor: getComputedStyle(document.documentElement)
    .getPropertyValue("--focus-ring-color"),
  // etc.
};
```

Then your own components reference those tokens. Steam's visual redesign is reflected automatically through the variables, but Valve can completely restructure their component tree without touching your components at all. Your `<Panel>` is just a `div` with the right background color — it doesn't care what Valve does with their `Panel_3RNGB` class.

---

## Putting It Together: The Resilience Stack

```
Plugin author imports @your-loader/ui
        ↓
Stable abstraction layer (your code, never breaks)
        ↓
Multi-strategy lazy finders (tries 3-4 ways to find each module)
        ↓
Webpack interceptor (patches code before execution where needed)
        ↓
SteamOS update happens...
        ↓
CI job detects broken finders, files issue
        ↓
Loader gets a small update fixing just the broken finders
        ↓
Plugins get nothing pushed to them — they were shielded
```

The end goal is that a SteamOS update should require a loader patch of maybe 20-50 lines touching `steam-modules.ts`, and zero plugin authors need to do anything. That's the actual deliverable of all this architecture work.
